Fiction from the Archives

Donald Barthelme

Selected Stories

  • The Balloon

    “It was agreed that since the meaning of the balloon could never be known absolutely, extended discussion was pointless.”

  • The School

    “They asked me, where did they go? The trees, the salamander, the tropical fish, Edgar, the poppas and mommas, Matthew and Tony?”

  • The Indian Uprising

    “But it is you I want now, here in the middle of this Uprising, with the streets yellow and threatening.”
Photograph by Ben Martin / Getty
“Nobody in the world had seen writing like this,” Roger Angell, Donald Barthelme’s editor at The New Yorker, told his biographer. A balloon occupies Manhattan, King Kong shows up at a party, zombies shop for wives: surreal, antic, absurd, playful, parodic, flooded with allusions, Barthelme’s stories (more than a hundred of which appeared in the magazine before his death, in 1989) spiral across the page like a tornado of imagery and meaning.
